           SHORT="2.6 kernel with Con Kolivas Overloaded patches"
cat << EOF
2.6 kernel with Con Kolivas patches to improve system responsiveness.
The CKO patchset adds the following patches to the CK patchset:

    * Reiser4 filesystem, 
    * SHFS support (secure SHell FileSystem), 
    * Supermount, 
    * UML host skas3 support (includes SYSEMU), 
    * Alan Cox's -ac patchset (mostly IDE updates now), 
    * Jeff Garzik's libata updates, 
    * ACPI4Linux update, 
    * ALSA update, 
    * Linux Bluetooth protocol stack, 
    * Bttv update, 
    * Vesa-tng and fbsplash, 
    * LIRC (Linux Infrared Remote Control) support, 
    * Software Suspend, 
    * Inotify, 
    * config hz (variable HZ setting)

Linux is a clone of the Unix kernel, written from scratch by Linus
Torvalds with assistance from a loosely-knit team of hackers across the
Net. It aims towards POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance. It
has all the features you would expect in a modern fully-fledged Unix
kernel, including true multitasking, virtual memory, shared libraries,
demand loading, shared copy-on-write executables, proper memory
management, and TCP/IP networking.
EOF
